-- ── CrowdSec ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CrowdSec is an open-source, crowdsourced intrusion detection and threat intelligence platform that shares real-time malicious IP data across its global community.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Montrouge (Paris), France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CrowdSec Review 2026: Crowdsourced Threat Intel & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CrowdSec is an open-source, crowdsourced IDS that blocks malicious IPs using threat data shared by a global community. See features, pricing, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CrowdSec is an open-source, crowdsourced cybersecurity platform that detects and blocks malicious IP addresses by pooling real-time attack signals from a global network of users. The company was founded in January 2020 by Philippe Humeau, Laurent Soubrevilla, and Thibault Koechlin, and is headquartered in Montrouge, a suburb of Paris, France, with a team of roughly 35 to 40 employees as of 2026. CrowdSec has raised more than $21 million in total funding, including a €14 million (approximately $14 million) Series A round announced in October 2022, positioning it as a well-capitalized European cybersecurity startup competing in the threat intelligence and intrusion prevention space. The core idea behind CrowdSec is participative security: when one organization running the CrowdSec Security Engine detects an attack, such as a brute-force login attempt, a web scraping bot, or an exploit scan, that signal is anonymized and shared with the wider CrowdSec network, and in return every other participant receives an updated blocklist reflecting attacks seen anywhere in the community. This crowdsourced model is explicitly modeled on the idea of a neighborhood watch for the internet, and CrowdSec markets itself as the first crowdsourced cyber threat intelligence (CTI) solution of its kind. The core CrowdSec Security Engine is released under the MIT open-source license and can be self-hosted for free, installed on Linux servers, containers, or edge devices to analyze logs in real time using configurable detection scenarios. Detected threats trigger local remediation through modular components called bouncers, which integrate with firewalls (iptables, nftables, pf), reverse proxies and web servers (Nginx, Apache, Traefik, HAProxy), CDNs, WordPress, and cloud provider security groups to automatically block or challenge malicious traffic. CrowdSec has reported that its software has been installed more than 100,000 times across roughly 175 countries, with users ranging from individual server administrators and small businesses to governments, e-commerce companies, and financial institutions. Beyond the free, self-hosted core engine, CrowdSec runs a hosted management layer called the CrowdSec Console, which gives administrators a centralized dashboard to monitor alerts, manage multiple Security Engines, and configure remediation policies across a fleet of servers; this is offered under a free Community tier as well as a paid Console Premium tier priced on a pay-as-you-grow basis per enrolled Security Engine, adding features like the Premium Community Blocklist, surge alert notifications, extended alert retention, and multi-channel notification integrations. CrowdSec also monetizes its aggregated threat data directly: its Platinum Blocklists product, aimed at network and infrastructure teams that want to block malicious traffic without running the full engine, starts at roughly $1,900 per month for small and midsize businesses and includes industry-specific, technology-specific, and country-specific blocklists as well as a dedicated AI-crawler blocklist, with simple integrations for common firewalls and CDNs. Separately, CrowdSec offers an IP Reputation and Cyber Threat Intelligence (CTI) API for developers who want to enrich their own security tooling with contextual data on IP addresses, starting around $49 per month for 5,000 queries and scaling up to bespoke enterprise API quotas and local, on-premises replication of the CTI dataset starting near $9,000 per month for organizations with strict latency or data residency requirements. The CTI product returns more than 30 contextual criteria per IP, including industry and country targeting, connection type, MITRE ATT&CK technique classification, and hourly updated behavioral scoring. CrowdSec differentiates itself from traditional, single-organization intrusion prevention tools like Fail2ban by turning detection into a collective, real-time defense network rather than something each server has to learn on its own, and it differentiates itself from commercial threat intelligence vendors like Recorded Future or Spamhaus by being open source at its core and driven by community-contributed signals rather than proprietary honeypots alone. Typical users include DevOps and platform engineering teams protecting self-managed infrastructure, managed service providers securing client environments, SaaS companies wanting to reduce credential-stuffing and bot traffic, and security teams that want to complement existing firewalls and WAFs with continuously updated, crowdsourced blocklists. Its open-core business model, in which the detection engine is free and open source while the console, premium blocklists, and CTI API are commercial, mirrors the approach used by other successful open-source security and infrastructure companies, and it allows CrowdSec to grow its user base and its collective threat data simultaneously, since every new free user who deploys the engine strengthens the blocklists that paying customers rely on. CrowdSec also maintains a public hub of community-contributed detection scenarios, parsers, and collections tailored to specific applications and services, letting users extend the engine to protect additional software without writing detection logic from scratch, which further reinforces the community-driven nature of the project. CrowdSec's growth strategy has relied heavily on this community flywheel: because the free Security Engine is genuinely useful on its own for blocking common attacks, the company has been able to build a large installed base first and monetize a smaller share of that base through premium blocklists, the CTI API, and enterprise console features, an approach that has helped it expand into 175-plus countries without the marketing spend a purely closed-source competitor would typically require.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '521d7edd-be93-4cc5-b678-97bf55389e62';

