-- ── CryptPad ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CryptPad is an open-source, end-to-end encrypted office suite offering documents, spreadsheets, kanban boards, whiteboards, and forms with zero-knowledge privacy.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1-10 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$and 20+ other community-translated languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CryptPad Review 2026: Encrypted Collaboration Suite$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CryptPad is an open-source, end-to-end encrypted office suite for docs, sheets, and forms. See features, self-hosting options, and CryptPad pricing plans.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CryptPad is an open-source, end-to-end encrypted collaboration suite that provides rich text documents, spreadsheets, presentations, a code and markdown editor, kanban boards, a whiteboard, forms, and cloud file storage, all designed so that the server operator never has access to readable user data. The project originated from work by Caleb James De Lisle, an engineer formerly employed by XWiki SAS, a Paris-based company that has built open-source software for more than two decades. CryptPad grew out of a research grant that XWiki SAS received from BPI France to explore real-time collaborative editing, and De Lisle developed ChainPad, a conflict-free replicated data type (CRDT) based algorithm that allows multiple users to edit a document simultaneously while all synchronization data remains encrypted before it ever leaves the browser. Today CryptPad is maintained by a dedicated team inside XWiki SAS, informally called the CryptPad Squad, led by David Benque, with roughly seven core team members as of recent years. Technically, CryptPad's defining characteristic is its zero-knowledge architecture: encryption and decryption happen entirely client-side in the user's browser using keys derived from the user's credentials, so the server that hosts and synchronizes documents only ever stores and transmits encrypted ciphertext. This means CryptPad administrators, including the operators of the flagship public instance, cannot read document contents, see file names, or access account passwords even if compelled to, which is a meaningful differentiator from mainstream office suites like Google Workspace or Microsoft 365, where the provider technically has access to unencrypted content on its servers. CryptPad is released as free and open-source software, with its source code hosted publicly on GitHub, and it can be self-hosted at no cost by any individual or organization with the technical capacity to run a Node.js-based server, giving privacy-conscious users, activists, journalists, and organizations subject to strict data-sovereignty requirements full control over where their data lives. For users who do not want to self-host, XWiki operates a flagship public instance at cryptpad.fr offering free accounts with baseline storage, plus optional individual paid plans ranging from about €5 to €100 per month for additional storage and priority support. Organizations that want a managed or dedicated deployment can purchase CryptPad Enterprise plans, which start around €1,500 per year and scale through several tiers: a Mini tier for 50 users and 100 GB of storage at roughly €3,000 per year, a Small tier for 250 users and 200 GB at about €6,000 per year, a Medium tier for 500 users and 500 GB at about €12,500 per year, and a Large tier for 1,000 users and 1 TB at about €25,000 per year, with all enterprise tiers including SSO integration, managed or on-premise hosting, and support; education and nonprofit organizations receive a 50% discount on these enterprise rates. This layered model, free open-source core plus paid hosting and support, mirrors the open-core approach used by many privacy-focused infrastructure companies and allows CryptPad to sustain development while keeping the underlying software freely available to anyone. CryptPad has gained particular attention in public-sector and privacy-sensitive contexts; reporting in 2025 noted that United Nations personnel had begun piloting CryptPad as an alternative to Google Workspace for internal collaboration, reflecting growing institutional interest in sovereign, encrypted alternatives to major US cloud office suites, particularly within European public administrations and organizations bound by GDPR or similar data-protection regimes. CryptPad's most direct competitors include Nextcloud (particularly Nextcloud Office/Collabora), Cryptee, Skiff (before its 2024 shutdown and acquisition by Notion), Proton Drive and Proton Docs, and, at a broader level, mainstream suites like Google Workspace and Microsoft 365 that CryptPad positions itself as a privacy-respecting alternative to. Typical CryptPad users include privacy advocates, journalists and NGOs handling sensitive information, educational institutions, government agencies with data-sovereignty mandates, and small teams or open-source projects that want collaborative documents without depending on a US-based cloud provider. Because CryptPad is open source, self-hostable, and does not rely on advertising or data monetization for revenue, its business model depends on a mix of donations, paid hosting on the flagship instance, and enterprise contracts, which keeps its incentives aligned with user privacy rather than data collection. The project also publishes its source code publicly and accepts community contributions, which allows independent security researchers to audit its cryptographic implementation rather than trusting the encryption claims of a closed-source vendor, an assurance that is particularly important for organizations subject to strict compliance or data-protection obligations. CryptPad additionally supports fine-grained sharing controls, including view-only and edit links with expiration options, and password-protected access to individual documents, so teams can collaborate with external parties without granting them a full account or broader access to a shared workspace. Because CryptPad is developed by an established open-source company rather than an anonymous or purely volunteer-run project, it benefits from more predictable release cycles and long-term maintenance commitments than many smaller privacy tools, which is one reason institutional adopters such as public administrations have been willing to evaluate it as a genuine production alternative to mainstream commercial office suites rather than treating it purely as an experimental or hobbyist tool.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '41beb071-a49d-4ab2-b0b3-1264edc2d746';

