-- ── Cube ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cube is an open-core semantic layer platform that defines metrics and access rules once and exposes them via SQL, REST, and GraphQL APIs for BI, apps, and AI agents.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$51-100 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cube Review 2026: Semantic Layer Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cube is an open-source, headless semantic layer for BI, embedded analytics, and AI agents. Compare Cube Core vs Cube Cloud pricing, features, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cube is a semantic layer platform that lets data teams define metrics, dimensions, joins, and access-control rules once in code and then expose that governed data model to any downstream consumer, business intelligence tools, embedded analytics inside customer-facing applications, spreadsheets, and, increasingly, AI agents and large language models, through SQL, REST, and GraphQL APIs. The company behind Cube, Cube Dev, Inc., was founded in 2016 by Artyom Keydunov and Pavel Tiunov and is headquartered in San Francisco, California. The product began as Cube.js, a JavaScript framework originally built out of an earlier project called Statsbot before the founders pivoted specifically toward the semantic layer category, and it has since been rebranded simply as Cube. Cube Dev has raised a total of roughly $47 million across three funding rounds, including a $25 million round that included Databricks as a strategic investor and partner, reflecting the growing interest of large data-platform vendors in the semantic-layer space as a neutral governance layer that sits between raw data warehouses and the tools people actually use to query that data. Architecturally, Cube is split into an open-source core and a commercial cloud product. Cube Core is released under a permissive license, Apache 2.0 for the backend server and MIT for portions of the client libraries, is available on GitHub with roughly 20,000 stars, and can be self-hosted for free. Cube Core lets engineers define a data model in code (YAML or JavaScript/TypeScript) describing metrics, dimensions, pre-aggregations, and row- or column-level access policies, connects to virtually any SQL data warehouse or database (Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift, Postgres, ClickHouse, Databricks, and dozens of others), and then serves that model out through a REST API, a GraphQL API, and a Postgres-compatible SQL API that lets existing BI tools like Tableau, Power BI, and Looker Studio connect to Cube as if it were a database. Cube Cloud is the company's managed, enterprise-grade product, adding a hosted semantic layer IDE, Cube Store (a specialized caching and pre-aggregation engine that dramatically speeds up query performance), workbooks and dashboards for exploring the semantic layer directly, agentic analytics features that let AI copilots and chat interfaces query governed metrics rather than raw tables (reducing the risk of an LLM hallucinating incorrect numbers), production orchestration, monitoring, and role-based access controls. Cube's central positioning in the market is as a headless, API-first semantic layer, meaning it deliberately does not ship its own dashboarding or visualization front end, instead focusing on being the single governed source of metric definitions that any number of downstream BI tools, internal apps, or AI systems can share, which avoids the common problem of different teams calculating the same metric differently in different tools. Cube's pricing follows a freemium, open-core structure. The Free tier of Cube Cloud is free forever and aimed at hobbyists and small projects, including data source connections, the semantic layer IDE, workbooks, and dashboards. The Starter tier costs $40 per developer per month plus usage-based consumption billed in Cube Compute Units at roughly $0.10 per unit, with a $99 per month minimum, and adds extended agent limits, premium LLM access, unlimited workbooks, and production deployment. The Premium tier costs $80 per developer per month plus consumption at roughly $0.25 per Cube Compute Unit with a $10,000 annual commitment, and adds Explorer and Viewer user roles, embedded dashboards and analytics chat, unlimited queries, a 99.95% uptime SLA, custom domains, and multi-cluster deployment; additional Explorer seats cost $40 per user per month and Viewer seats cost $20 per user per month on Premium and above. The Enterprise tier is custom-priced and adds a 99.99% uptime SLA, dedicated single-tenant infrastructure, bring-your-own-cloud (BYOC) deployment, custom LLM integration, SSO/SAML, granular workspace access controls, and a DAX API specifically for connecting Cube to Microsoft Power BI. Cube's primary competitors include dbt Labs' Semantic Layer (built on the MetricFlow engine), Looker's LookML modeling layer from Google Cloud, AtScale, and Kyligence, and it is frequently discussed as an alternative or complement to building a custom metrics layer by hand inside a data warehouse. Typical Cube users are data engineering and analytics engineering teams at software companies that need to embed analytics or dashboards inside their own product for customers, as well as data platform teams at larger organizations that want a single governed definition of business metrics shared consistently across Tableau, Power BI, internal tools, and, more recently, AI chat assistants and agents that need to query trustworthy numbers rather than raw, ungoverned tables. Cube publishes extensive documentation and maintains an active open-source community around Cube Core, and the company has positioned the rise of AI copilots and natural-language analytics as a major tailwind for the semantic-layer category generally, arguing that a governed metrics layer becomes even more important once an LLM, rather than a human analyst who can sanity-check a number, is the one writing and executing queries against a company's data.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7ae35df8-1db0-4f11-b030-bac3223a2cbe';

