-- ── Culture Amp ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Culture Amp is an employee experience platform for engagement surveys, performance management, and people analytics, backed by research-driven people science.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2009, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1,000-2,000 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Melbourne, Australia$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$and multiple additional languages via platform localization$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Culture Amp Review 2026: Features, Pricing & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Culture Amp is an employee experience platform for engagement surveys and performance management. See features, pricing tiers, and top alternatives for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Culture Amp is an employee experience platform used by human resources and people teams to run engagement surveys, manage performance reviews and goal-setting, and turn employee feedback into people analytics that inform organizational decisions. The company was founded in 2009 in Melbourne, Australia, by Didier Elzinga, Doug English, Rod Hamilton, and Jon Williams, and it remains headquartered in Melbourne while operating additional offices in the United States (including San Francisco), the United Kingdom, and Germany to serve its global customer base. Culture Amp has raised approximately $258 million in total venture funding from investors including Sequoia Capital, Index Ventures, Blackbird Ventures, and Felicis Ventures, and reached unicorn status after closing a $150 million Series F round in July 2021 co-led by Sequoia Capital China and TDM Growth Partners, which valued the company at $1.5 billion. As of recent reporting, Culture Amp serves more than 6,500 companies and over 25 million employees worldwide, ranging from fast-growing technology startups to large multinational enterprises, making it one of the most widely adopted platforms in the employee engagement and performance management category. Culture Amp differentiates itself from generic survey tools by grounding its product in what it calls people science, drawing on organizational behavior research and industrial-organizational (I/O) psychology to design scientifically validated survey questions and provide benchmarking data across industries, company sizes, and regions so HR teams can compare their own engagement scores against relevant peer groups rather than guessing at what a good score looks like. The platform is organized around several core products that can be purchased individually or together: Engage, which covers employee engagement surveys, pulse surveys, and always-on feedback channels; Perform, which covers performance management workflows including goal-setting (OKRs), continuous feedback, 360-degree reviews, and structured performance review cycles; and Develop, an add-on focused on skills mapping and career development planning. Culture Amp also offers People Science Consulting as a premium add-on, giving customers direct access to Culture Amp's in-house researchers and organizational psychologists for strategic advisory work, and it has layered generative AI capabilities into the platform through a feature called AI Coach, which helps managers prepare for difficult conversations, summarize open-ended survey comments, and draft development plans. All Culture Amp plans share a baseline of enterprise-oriented capabilities, including single sign-on (SSO), data encryption, integrations with common HRIS platforms (such as Workday, BambooHR, and ADP), multilingual survey support for global workforces, and SOC 2 compliance for data security. Culture Amp does not publish specific list prices publicly; instead, pricing depends on the number of employees at the customer organization, which specific products are purchased (Engage alone, Perform alone, or the combined platform), and the service tier selected, with all contracts billed annually rather than monthly. The company segments its go-to-market and support model by company size: organizations under roughly 200 employees receive group-based Customer Success support with 24/5 chat and email access; mid-market organizations with 200 to 999 employees get a dedicated one-on-one Customer Success partnership along with expert-led implementation project management; and enterprise organizations with 1,000 or more employees receive additional services such as manager and executive training, one-on-one and group coaching, and dedicated support resources. Third-party pricing aggregators have estimated a starting price in the range of roughly $30 per employee per month for smaller deployments, though prospective customers must request a formal quote or book a demo with Culture Amp's sales team to get an accurate number for their organization. Culture Amp's primary competitors in the employee experience and engagement category include Lattice, which pairs performance reviews with engagement surveys in a single system; 15Five, known for continuous listening, manager enablement, and simpler pulse-survey workflows; Leapsome; Qualtrics EmployeeXM; and Microsoft Viva Glint, which has a natural advantage for organizations already standardized on the Microsoft 365 ecosystem. Typical Culture Amp customers are HR, People Operations, and Talent teams at mid-market and enterprise companies that want research-backed survey methodology, robust benchmarking data, and a combined engagement-plus-performance platform rather than piecing together separate point solutions for surveys and performance reviews. The company also publishes original research and thought leadership through its people science team, including periodic reports on workplace trends and benchmarking data, which it uses both as a marketing channel and as an input into how it designs and validates new survey questions and product features. Over time Culture Amp has broadened its platform beyond its original engagement-survey product into adjacent areas such as performance management and skills development, reflecting a strategy of becoming a single system that spans more of the employee lifecycle rather than remaining a point solution focused only on annual engagement surveys. Because Culture Amp sells to HR buyers who are themselves evaluated on measurable outcomes like retention and engagement scores, the company has emphasized case studies and outcome data in its marketing and sales process, positioning its research-backed methodology as a way for HR teams to justify programmatic investment in engagement and performance initiatives to their own executive leadership and boards.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8260c82f-10fa-4ece-b662-6c99bd5967eb';

