-- ── CUPS ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CUPS (Common Unix Printing System) is a free, open-source printing system for Linux and Unix-like operating systems, using the Internet Printing Protocol.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1997, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CUPS: The Open-Source Unix Printing System Explained$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CUPS is the free, open-source Common Unix Printing System used by Linux, macOS, and Unix. Learn its history, architecture, licensing, and how it works.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CUPS, originally an acronym for the Common UNIX Printing System and now used simply as CUPS, is a free and open-source printing system that provides a standards-based printing architecture for Linux and other Unix-like operating systems. Development began in 1997 by Michael Sweet, who at the time owned a company called Easy Software Products, with the first public beta releases appearing in 1999. The project's original name was shortened to just CUPS starting with version 1.4 because of legal concerns over use of the trademarked term UNIX. Unlike its predecessor systems, which relied on the older Line Printer Daemon (LPD) protocol, CUPS was built around the Internet Printing Protocol (IPP), an HTTP-based standard that offered better support for modern network printers, richer printer capability discovery, and fewer vendor compatibility problems than LPD. This design choice helped CUPS become the de facto default printing system on nearly every major Linux distribution during the 2000s, replacing older printing subsystems like LPRng across the ecosystem. CUPS gained a second, very significant distribution channel in March 2002, when Apple Inc. adopted it as the underlying printing system for Mac OS X 10.2 (Jaguar), a role it has continued to play in every subsequent version of macOS. Apple's involvement deepened considerably in February 2007, when the company hired Michael Sweet, CUPS's chief developer, and formally acquired the CUPS source code and trademark, effectively bringing the project's primary development in-house at Apple while keeping it available under an open-source license. Apple continued to steward CUPS development for over a decade, until December 2019, when Michael Sweet announced he was leaving Apple. In 2020, stewardship of CUPS's upstream development transitioned to OpenPrinting, a community and industry organization focused on Linux and Unix printing standards, which now maintains the project's GitHub repository and drives ongoing feature work, including the CUPS 3.x generation of the software and related components such as libcups (the client-side CUPS API library), cups-local (a local server component for CUPS 3), and PAPPL, a framework for building modern IPP-based printer applications. CUPS is licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0, with an added exception clause that permits linking against software licensed only under GPLv2, a licensing approach shared by most of OpenPrinting's related projects. Architecturally, CUPS functions as a modular printing system composed of a background scheduler daemon (cupsd in the CUPS 2.x line, with CUPS 3.x moving toward a more distributed local-server model), a set of filters that convert documents from application-native formats into formats a given printer understands, backends that handle the actual transmission of print jobs to devices over USB, network IPP, or other connections, and a web-based administrative interface for configuring printers and monitoring queues. Applications and command-line tools interact with CUPS through its API and through standard Unix printing commands such as lp and lpr, both of which CUPS maintains for backward compatibility with older Unix printing conventions even though its internal protocol implementation is IPP-based. Because CUPS is free, open-source, and bundled by default with virtually every major Linux distribution as well as macOS, it does not have a commercial pricing model, a company headquarters, or a conventional employee count in the way a SaaS product would; it is best understood as critical, largely invisible infrastructure software maintained by a small, community-driven engineering effort under the OpenPrinting umbrella rather than as a company with a go-to-market or sales organization. There is no direct commercial competitor in the same sense as SaaS products, since CUPS effectively is the standard printing system for open-source operating systems, though it can be contrasted with proprietary printing subsystems built into Windows (the Windows Print Spooler) and with printer-manufacturer-specific driver software. For end users, CUPS is largely invisible, working behind the scenes whenever a Linux or macOS system prints a document, but for system administrators and developers it exposes a documented API, a web administration interface typically reachable on port 631, and configuration files that allow fine-grained control over shared printers, access permissions, and job queue management in both home and enterprise network environments. CUPS also underpins network printer discovery on Unix-like systems through protocols such as DNS-SD/Bonjour and IPP Everywhere, which lets modern printers advertise their capabilities on a local network so that client machines can add and configure them automatically without installing manufacturer-specific driver packages. This driverless printing model, sometimes referred to as universal printing, has become increasingly important as the printing industry has standardized around IPP, and it is one of the main areas of ongoing work in the CUPS 3.x generation of the software led by OpenPrinting, alongside improved support for containerized and sandboxed environments where a traditional system-wide print daemon is not always practical to run. Because CUPS predates almost every modern Linux distribution and desktop environment in its current form, it has also become a stable, well-understood integration point that printer manufacturers, distribution maintainers, and desktop projects like GNOME and KDE all build against, which is part of why it has remained the de facto standard rather than being displaced by a newer alternative despite periodic community discussion about modernizing the Unix printing stack.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0fe96227-1d6d-4bd6-83ce-4ceea48aafd2';

