-- ── Cursor ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cursor is an AI-native code editor built by Anysphere that uses agentic AI to write, edit, and review code across a codebase from natural-language instructions.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$300+ employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cursor AI Code Editor Review 2026: Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cursor is Anysphere's AI-native code editor with agentic coding, Tab autocomplete, and Bugbot review. Compare Cursor's Hobby, Individual, and Teams pricing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cursor is an AI-native code editor built by Anysphere, Inc., a San Francisco-based software company founded in 2022 by MIT students and dropouts Michael Truell, Sualeh Asif, Aman Sanger, and Arvid Lunnemark, who left the company in October 2025. Cursor is built as a fork of Microsoft's open-source Visual Studio Code editor, which lets it retain compatibility with the existing VS Code extension ecosystem and keyboard shortcuts while layering deeply integrated, codebase-aware AI capabilities on top. Rather than treating AI assistance as a chat sidebar bolted onto a traditional editor, Cursor is designed around an agentic workflow in which the AI can read and search across an entire codebase, propose and apply multi-file edits, run terminal commands, and iterate on its own output based on test results or error messages, all initiated from natural-language instructions. Core product capabilities include Tab, a predictive, multi-line autocomplete feature that suggests entire edits rather than single lines; Agent (formerly and still sometimes called Composer), a more autonomous mode that can plan and execute multi-step coding tasks across many files with limited supervision; Bugbot, an automated code-review feature that flags likely bugs and issues in pull requests; and Cloud Agents, which let coding agents run asynchronously in the background rather than only inside the local editor session. Cursor supports the Model Context Protocol (MCP) for connecting external tools and data sources to its agents, and it gives users access to multiple frontier AI models from providers including Anthropic, OpenAI, and Google, alongside Anysphere's own in-house Composer model, rather than locking users into a single model provider. Anysphere's funding history has been unusually fast even by the standards of the current AI boom: after an $8 million seed round in October 2023 led by the OpenAI Startup Fund, the company raised a $60 million Series A in 2024 at roughly a $400 million valuation, then a $900 million Series C in June 2025 led by Thrive Capital at a $9.9 billion valuation, followed just months later by a $2.3 billion Series D in November 2025 co-led by Accel and Coatue that pushed its valuation to $29.3 billion. In early 2026 the company was reportedly in talks to raise more than $2 billion at a valuation above $50 billion with participation from Andreessen Horowitz, Thrive Capital, and Nvidia as a strategic investor. On June 16, 2026, SpaceX announced it would acquire Anysphere in an all-stock deal valuing the company at approximately $60 billion, with the transaction expected to close in the third quarter of 2026 and Cursor to operate as part of a SpaceXAI subsidiary; as of the announcement, the deal had not yet closed. Cursor's revenue growth has been described as the fastest ramp of any application-layer software company to date, reportedly crossing $100 million in annual recurring revenue in January 2025, surpassing $500 million by June 2025, exceeding $1 billion by November 2025, and passing $2 billion by February 2026. Cursor's pricing follows a freemium model with four tiers. The Hobby plan is free and offers limited Agent requests and limited Tab completions with no credit card required, aimed at developers trying the product casually. The Individual plan costs $16 per month and adds extended Agent limits, generous access to models like Grok and Composer, access to frontier models generally, support for MCP servers, skills, and hooks, cloud agents, and usage-based Bugbot billing. The Teams plan costs $32 per user per month and adds centralized team billing and administration, a team marketplace for sharing internal rules and plugins, agentic code review through Bugbot, cloud agents with shared team context, usage analytics, team-wide privacy mode, and SAML/OIDC single sign-on. The Enterprise plan is custom-priced and adds pooled usage across the organization, invoice and purchase-order billing, SCIM-based seat management, granular controls over repository, model, and MCP access, network and browser controls for agents, audit logging, service accounts, an AI code-tracking API, and priority support. In July 2025, Cursor faced user backlash after changing how its (then-named) Pro plan handled usage-based billing, leading to unexpectedly large charges for some customers; the company responded by adjusting its limits and issuing refunds. Cursor's primary competitors include GitHub Copilot, Windsurf (formerly Codeium), JetBrains AI Assistant, Amazon Q Developer, Replit, Zed, and Anthropic's own Claude Code command-line agent, and Cursor is generally considered one of the category-defining products in the AI-native code editor and coding-agent space that emerged in 2023 and 2024. Typical Cursor users are professional software engineers and engineering teams at startups and larger companies who want AI assistance embedded directly into their primary development environment rather than as a separate chat tool, ranging from individual developers on the free or Individual plan up to large engineering organizations on Enterprise contracts requiring centralized governance and audit controls. Cursor has also become closely associated with the broader shift in software development toward AI-assisted and increasingly autonomous coding workflows, with its rapid revenue growth frequently cited by industry analysts as evidence of how quickly professional developers have been willing to pay for AI tools that materially speed up day-to-day coding work rather than merely offering novelty chat assistance.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '693230a0-d462-46dc-9108-9752df61caba';

